`emit/` renders Pass-A tables (types, constructs) into the two C++ header artifacts the javelin-ext build consumes: the replay dictionary data header and a golden-test header pinning that dictionary against the Rust reference walker. Depending on this subtree gets you `emit_data_header` and `emit_test_header`, both `Result<String, ExpandError>`-returning, self-contained header generators — callers don't need to know about stroke encoding or sampling internals.

The shared coupling is `stroke_mask()` in mod.rs: both data.rs (encoding real corpus strokes) and test.rs (encoding sampled sequences via `mask_array`) depend on it, and its bit layout must stay in lockstep with javelin's `StrokeBitIndex`. Changing the key order tables (`LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER`) breaks both headers simultaneously. `c_escape()` is the other shared primitive, used by both data.rs (construct text) and test.rs (golden row text) to produce valid C string literal bodies — a change to escaping rules must be verified against both emitters.

sample.rs is upstream of test.rs only: it produces the sampled stroke sequences (`sample_sequences`) that test.rs walks and encodes; data.rs never touches sampling. mod.rs supplies primitives (`stroke_mask`, `c_escape`) to both data.rs and test.rs but emits nothing itself.

Invariant spanning the subtree: the `uint32_t` mask format (6-digit hex, `0x`/`u` wrapping) and struct field layouts in both headers' preambles must match the C++ struct definitions `javelin-ext` expects — this isn't enforced by the compiler, only by the golden test round-trip.